{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1779039171656,"sessionID":"ses_1c900d483ffe3X7x4o8qKel0y4","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_bab621327fa46823","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/pruiz/Develop/mine/CodeCome-e2e-testing/AGENTS.md"},"output":"<path>/Users/pruiz/Develop/mine/CodeCome-e2e-testing/AGENTS.md</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: # CodeCome Agent Instructions\n2: \n3: You are working inside a CodeCome vulnerability research workspace.\n4: \n5: CodeCome is an AI-assisted vulnerability research workflow. Its purpose is to help inspect source code, identify attack surfaces, create structured vulnerability hypotheses, perform counter-analysis, validate findings inside a sandbox, and produce reviewable Markdown reports.\n6: \n7: ## Prime directive\n8: \n9: Produce durable artifacts.\n10: \n11: Important security claims must be written to files under `itemdb/`, not left only in chat history or transient run output.\n12: \n13: ## Workspace layout\n14: \n15: - `codecome.yml`: project configuration and audit settings.\n16: - `src/`: target source code to audit.\n17: - `sandbox/`: sandboxed execution and validation environment.\n18: - `itemdb/`: file-based finding database, notes, reports, and evidence.\n19: - `itemdb/notes/`: reconnaissance notes and target model.\n20: - `itemdb/findings/PENDING/`: candidate findings requiring validation.\n21: - `itemdb/findings/CONFIRMED/`: validated findings with evidence.\n22: - `itemdb/findings/EXPLOITED/`: confirmed findings with demonstrated real-world impact.\n23: - `itemdb/findings/REJECTED/`: disproven or non-actionable findings.\n24: - `itemdb/findings/DUPLICATE/`: duplicate findings.\n25: - `itemdb/evidence/`: validation evidence, grouped by finding id.\n26: - `itemdb/reports/`: generated Markdown reports.\n27: - `runs/`: run prompts, summaries, and transcripts when available.\n28: - `templates/`: required Markdown templates.\n29: - `tools/`: helper scripts.\n30: - `.opencode/agents/`: specialized agent definitions.\n31: - `.opencode/skills/`: reusable skills.\n32: \n33: ## General rules\n34: \n35: 1. Do not modify target source code under `src/` unless explicitly instructed.\n36: 2. **Never modify project orchestration or configuration files (`codecome.yml`, `AGENTS.md`, Makefile, `.opencode/` configs, etc.) unless explicitly instructed. Your role is to audit or validate the target, not to reconfigure the project.**\n37: 3. Prefer reading and analyzing before writing.\n38: 3. Do not create vague findings.\n39: 4. Do not mark a finding as confirmed without evidence.\n40: 5. Always distinguish hypothesis from confirmed vulnerability.\n41: 6. Always include counter-analysis for every finding.\n42: 7. Always include a validation plan for every finding.\n43: 8. Store validation evidence under `itemdb/evidence/<finding-id>/`.\n44: 9. Keep findings reviewable by humans.\n45: 10. Use precise file paths, function names, symbols, routes, commands, or configuration keys whenever possible.\n46: 11. If a target-specific skill applies, use it, but keep the core workflow target-agnostic.\n47: 12. Do not rely only on filenames, comments, benchmark labels, or directory names to claim a vulnerability.\n48: 13. NEVER use the absolute path `/tmp/` for any temporary files, downloads, or operations. The sandbox will reject `/tmp/`. Always use the workspace-relative `tmp/` directory.\n49: \n50: ## Local quality gate (no CI)\n51: \n52: This repository currently relies on local developer checks instead of CI.\n53: \n54: Before committing or pushing changes, run:\n55: \n56:     make tests\n57: \n58: This command runs `pytest` for `tests/` and then validates finding frontmatter using `tools/check-frontmatter.py`.\n59: \n60: ## Allowed write locations\n61: \n62: Unless explicitly instructed otherwise, write only under:\n63: \n64: - `itemdb/`\n65: - `runs/`\n66: - `sandbox/`\n67: - `templates/`\n68: - `tools/`\n69: - `tmp/`\n70: - `.opencode/`\n71: \n72: **IMPORTANT SANDBOX RULE:** Never use the absolute path `/tmp/` in any tool or shell command, as it will be rejected by the OpenCode sandbox. Instead, always use the workspace-relative `tmp/` directory for temporary files, downloads, or scratch space.\n73: \n74: Do not write into `src/` except for temporary instrumentation when explicitly authorized.\n75: \n76: ## Target-agnostic mindset\n77: \n78: The target under `src/` may be:\n79: \n80: - a web application,\n81: - a backend service,\n82: - a CLI tool,\n83: - a library,\n84: - a benchmark corpus,\n85: - infrastructure-as-code,\n86: - a mobile project,\n87: - a desktop app,\n88: - a firmware tree,\n89: - or a mixed repository.\n90: \n91: During reconnaissance, infer the target model before reporting vulnerabilities.\n92: \n93: ## Core phases\n94: \n95: ### Phase 1: Target reconnaissance\n96: \n97: Goal: understand the target.\n98: \n99: Create or update these files:\n100: \n101: - `itemdb/notes/target-profile.md`\n102: - `itemdb/notes/attack-surface.md`\n103: - `itemdb/notes/build-model.md`\n104: - `itemdb/notes/execution-model.md`\n105: - `itemdb/notes/trust-boundaries.md`\n106: - `itemdb/notes/data-flow.md`\n107: - `itemdb/notes/validation-model.md`\n108: - `itemdb/notes/interesting-files.md`\n109: - `itemdb/notes/security-assumptions.md`\n110: \n111: Do not create findings during reconnaissance unless there is an extremely obvious, high-confidence, security-relevant issue.\n112: \n113: ### Phase 2: Hypothesis generation\n114: \n115: Goal: create precise candidate findings.\n116: \n117: Write findings under:\n118: \n119: - `itemdb/findings/PENDING/`\n120: \n121: Each finding must:\n122: \n123: - use the template from `templates/finding.md` when available,\n124: - have a stable id,\n125: - identify affected code,\n126: - describe source-to-sink or trust-boundary reasoning,\n127: - explain attackability,\n128: - explain impact,\n129: - include validation plan,\n130: - include counter-analysis placeholder,\n131: - avoid generic claims.\n132: \n133: ### Phase 3: Counter-analysis\n134: \n135: Goal: disprove weak findings.\n136: \n137: For each finding under `PENDING`:\n138: \n139: - look for existing mitigations,\n140: - check reachability,\n141: - check attacker control,\n142: - check trust boundaries,\n143: - check framework protections,\n144: - check whether assumptions are false,\n145: - check for duplicates,\n146: - lower confidence when needed,\n147: - move clearly invalid findings to `REJECTED`,\n148: - move duplicates to `DUPLICATE`.\n149: \n150: ### Phase 4: Validation\n151: \n152: Goal: prove or disprove one finding at a time.\n153: \n154: Use `sandbox/` as the sandbox.\n155: \n156: Validation may use:\n157: \n158: - static proof,\n159: - unit test,\n160: - integration test,\n161: - runtime reproduction,\n162: - sanitizer output,\n163: - crash reproduction,\n164: - HTTP exploit,\n165: - CLI exploit,\n166: - crafted input file,\n167: - config-based trigger,\n168: - log evidence,\n169: - database evidence,\n170: - debugger trace,\n171: - benchmark oracle comparison.\n172: \n173: A finding may be marked `CONFIRMED` only when the evidence is clear and reproducible enough.\n174: \n175: Benchmark labels alone are not enough for `CONFIRMED`.\n176: \n177: ### Phase 5: Exploit development\n178: \n179: Goal: demonstrate real-world impact of confirmed vulnerabilities.\n180: \n181: For selected `CONFIRMED` findings, develop proof-of-concept exploits that show what an attacker can actually achieve. This phase answers the question developers always ask: \"So what? What can an attacker actually do with this?\"\n182: \n183: The exploiter agent:\n184: \n185: - starts from existing validation evidence,\n186: - escalates impact (crash to code execution, read to secret exfiltration, bypass to full admin access),\n187: - produces self-contained, reproducible PoC scripts,\n188: - writes clear impact narratives,\n189: - adjusts severity based on demonstrated impact,\n190: - stores exploitation artifacts under `itemdb/evidence/<finding-id>/exploits/`.\n191: \n192: A finding may be moved to `EXPLOITED` only when a working proof-of-concept demonstrates concrete impact beyond the initial validation.\n193: \n194: If exploitation is not feasible within the sandbox, the finding stays in `CONFIRMED` with a documented explanation.\n195: \n196: ### Phase 6: Reporting\n197: \n198: Goal: produce Markdown reports.\n199: \n200: Reports should include:\n201: \n202: - executive summary,\n203: - target summary,\n204: - methodology,\n205: - exploited findings (with demonstrated impact),\n206: - confirmed findings,\n207: - rejected/duplicate summary if useful,\n208: - evidence references,\n209: - limitations,\n210: - recommended next steps.\n211: \n212: ## Finding quality bar\n213: \n214: A valid finding must answer:\n215: \n216: - What is the vulnerable component?\n217: - Where is the affected code?\n218: - What is the attacker-controlled input?\n219: - What trust boundary is crossed?\n220: - What dangerous sink or security decision is reached?\n221: - Why existing controls are insufficient?\n222: - What is the impact?\n223: - How can it be validated?\n224: - What evidence confirms or rejects it?\n225: \n226: Do not create findings like:\n227: \n228: > Potential SQL injection may exist because the project uses SQL.\n229: \n230: Create findings like:\n231: \n232: > User-controlled `sort` reaches raw SQL `ORDER BY` construction in `SearchRepository.BuildQuery()` without allowlist validation.\n233: \n234: ## Confidence levels\n235: \n236: Use these confidence levels:\n237: \n238: - `LOW`: plausible but weak; assumptions are significant.\n239: - `MEDIUM`: credible source-to-sink or trust-boundary path exists.\n240: - `HIGH`: strong static evidence exists, but runtime validation is still pending.\n241: - `CONFIRMED`: validated with evidence.\n242: \n243: ## Severity levels\n244: \n245: Use these severity levels:\n246: \n247: - `CRITICAL`\n248: - `HIGH`\n249: - `MEDIUM`\n250: - `LOW`\n251: - `INFO`\n252: \n253: Do not over-focus on CVSS in the PoC. Prefer clear technical impact.\n254: \n255: ## Status values\n256: \n257: Use only these status values:\n258: \n259: - `PENDING`\n260: - `CONFIRMED`\n261: - `EXPLOITED`\n262: - `REJECTED`\n263: - `DUPLICATE`\n264: \n265: ## Evidence rules\n266: \n267: For each confirmed or exploited finding, create:\n268: \n269: - `itemdb/evidence/<finding-id>/README.md`\n270: \n271: Add relevant artifacts when available:\n272: \n273: - requests,\n274: - responses,\n275: - logs,\n276: - screenshots,\n277: - terminal output,\n278: - exploit scripts,\n279: - generated inputs,\n280: - sanitizer reports,\n281: - crash dumps,\n282: - debugger notes,\n283: - database state,\n284: - test output.\n285: \n286: For exploited findings, also create:\n287: \n288: - `itemdb/evidence/<finding-id>/exploits/README.md` (using `templates/exploit-readme.md`)\n289: \n290: With additional artifacts such as:\n291: \n292: - proof-of-concept exploit scripts,\n293: - crafted payloads,\n294: - captured output demonstrating impact,\n295: - impact logs.\n296: \n297: ## Validation safety rules\n298: \n299: The validator may freely experiment inside the sandbox environment under `sandbox/`.\n300: \n301: The validator may install packages, build code, run tools, reset test data, and execute proof-of-concept inputs inside the sandbox.\n302: \n303: The validator must not attack third-party systems.\n304: \n305: The validator must not exfiltrate secrets.\n306: \n307: The validator must not modify production systems.\n308: \n309: The validator must not perform destructive actions outside the local sandbox.\n310: \n311: ## Target-specific behavior\n312: \n313: Target-specific logic belongs in skills.\n314: \n315: Examples:\n316: \n317: - `.opencode/skills/c-cpp-security/`\n318: - `.opencode/skills/web-security/`\n319: - `.opencode/skills/dotnet-security/`\n320: - `.opencode/skills/php-security/`\n321: - `.opencode/skills/sql-injection/`\n322: - `.opencode/skills/juliet-benchmark/`\n323: - `.opencode/skills/iac-security/`\n324: \n325: If the target appears to match a skill, apply the skill, but do not hardcode the whole workflow around a single target type.\n326: \n327: ## Phase handoff protocol\n328: \n329: CodeCome phases are executed sequentially and orchestrated by the user via `make` commands.\n330: \n331: Each phase has readiness gates that must be satisfied before it can run:\n332: \n333: ### Phase 1 readiness\n334: \n335: - `src/` must contain target source code.\n336: - No other prerequisites.\n337: \n338: ### Phase 2 readiness\n339: \n340: - `itemdb/notes/target-profile.md` must exist.\n341: - `itemdb/notes/attack-surface.md` must exist.\n342: - At least one reconnaissance note file must exist under `itemdb/notes/`.\n343: \n344: ### Phase 3 readiness\n345: \n346: - At least one finding must exist under `itemdb/findings/PENDING/`.\n347: \n348: ### Phase 4 readiness\n349: \n350: - A specific finding ID must be provided (e.g., `CC-0001`).\n351: - The finding must be in `PENDING` status.\n352: \n353: ### Phase 5 readiness\n354: \n355: - A specific finding ID must be provided (e.g., `CC-0001`).\n356: - The finding must be in `CONFIRMED` status.\n357: - Validation evidence must exist under `itemdb/evidence/<finding-id>/`.\n358: \n359: ### Phase 6 readiness\n360: \n361: - At least one finding must exist in any status directory.\n362: \n363: ### Orchestration model\n364: \n365: The user drives phase transitions by running:\n366: \n367:     make phase-1                  # Reconnaissance\n368:     make phase-2                  # Hypothesis generation\n369:     make phase-3                  # Counter-analysis\n370:     make phase-4 FINDING=CC-0001  # Validate one finding\n371:     make phase-5 FINDING=CC-0001  # Develop exploit for one finding\n372:     make phase-6                  # Reporting\n373: \n374: Each `make` target checks readiness gates before invoking the corresponding agent.\n375: \n376: Phase 4 is invoked once per finding, not as a batch.\n377: Phase 5 is invoked once per finding, not as a batch.\n378: \n379: For convenience, `make validate-all` iterates over all `PENDING` findings sequentially.\n380: For convenience, `make exploit-all` iterates over all `CONFIRMED` findings sequentially.\n381: \n382: No automatic handoff occurs between phases. The user decides when to advance.\n383: \n384: ## Run summaries\n385: \n386: When practical, write a short run summary under `runs/`.\n387: \n388: Use the template: `templates/run-summary.md`\n389: \n390: A run summary should include:\n391: \n392: - date,\n393: - phase,\n394: - prompt or goal,\n395: - files read,\n396: - files created or modified,\n397: - findings created,\n398: - findings moved,\n399: - important assumptions,\n400: - next recommended step.\n401: \n402: ## License\n403: \n404: CodeCome is dual-licensed under your choice of:\n405: \n406: - GNU General Public License version 3 or later (`GPL-3.0-or-later`), or\n407: - GNU Affero General Public License version 3 or later (`AGPL-3.0-or-later`).\n408: \n409: SPDX expression: `GPL-3.0-or-later OR AGPL-3.0-or-later`.\n410: \n411: The files under `templates/sandboxes/` are an exception: they are\n412: licensed under the **MIT License** so they can be copied into user\n413: workspaces without imposing copyleft obligations on those user\n414: projects.\n415: \n416: See `LICENSE`, `AGPL-LICENSE`, `templates/sandboxes/LICENSE`, and\n417: `NOTICE`. Contributions are accepted under the terms described in\n418: `CONTRIBUTING.md`.\n419: \n420: Copyright (C) 2025-2026 Pablo Ruiz García &lt;pablo.ruiz@gmail.com&gt;.\n\n(End of file - total 420 lines)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"# CodeCome Agent Instructions\n\nYou are working inside a CodeCome vulnerability research workspace.\n\nCodeCome is an AI-assisted vulnerability research workflow. Its purpose is to help inspect source code, identify attack surfaces, create structured vulnerability hypotheses, perform counter-analysis, validate findings inside a sandbox, and produce reviewable Markdown reports.\n\n## Prime directive\n\nProduce durable artifacts.\n\nImportant security claims must be written to files under `itemdb/`, not left only in chat history or transient run output.\n\n## Workspace layout\n\n- `codecome.yml`: project configuration and audit settings.\n- `src/`: target source code to audit.\n- `sandbox/`: sandboxed execution and validation environment.\n- `itemdb/`: file-based finding database, notes, reports, and evidence.\n- `itemdb/notes/`: reconnaissance notes and target model.\n- `itemdb/findings/PENDING/`: candidate findings requiring validation.","truncated":false,"loaded":[]},"title":"AGENTS.md","time":{"start":1779039171640,"end":1779039171653}},"id":"prt_e36ff7434001MSrpijejKB6wM2","sessionID":"ses_1c900d483ffe3X7x4o8qKel0y4","messageID":"msg_e36ff3000001wcz7905lcImUAZ"}}
