{"type":"text","timestamp":1779039180861,"sessionID":"ses_1c900d483ffe3X7x4o8qKel0y4","part":{"id":"prt_e36ff7e5d0019HLVW1zu5bEXMb","messageID":"msg_e36ff7576001STkwn1Fu87q0ip","sessionID":"ses_1c900d483ffe3X7x4o8qKel0y4","type":"text","text":"Now let me read the skill files and agent definitions:\n","time":{"start":1779039174237,"end":1779039180855}}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1779039180865,"sessionID":"ses_1c900d483ffe3X7x4o8qKel0y4","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_9377f1df927487dc","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/pruiz/Develop/mine/CodeCome-e2e-testing/.opencode/agents/recon.md"},"output":"<path>/Users/pruiz/Develop/mine/CodeCome-e2e-testing/.opencode/agents/recon.md</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: # CodeCome Recon Agent\n2: \n3: You are the CodeCome Recon Agent.\n4: \n5: Your role is to perform target reconnaissance and attack surface recognition.\n6: \n7: You do not create vulnerability findings unless explicitly instructed or unless an issue is extremely obvious, high-confidence, and security-relevant.\n8: \n9: **You must NEVER modify `codecome.yml`, `AGENTS.md`, Makefile, or any other project orchestration or configuration file. Your role is to perform reconnaissance on the target, not to reconfigure the project.**\n10: \n11: Your main output is a target model under:\n12: \n13:     itemdb/notes/\n14: \n15: ## Required reading\n16: \n17: Before starting reconnaissance, read:\n18: \n19: - `AGENTS.md`\n20: - `codecome.yml`\n21: - `templates/target-recon.md`\n22: - `.opencode/skills/source-recon/SKILL.md`\n23: - `.opencode/skills/sandbox-bootstrap/SKILL.md`\n24: \n25: Also reference when writing run summaries:\n26: \n27: - `templates/run-summary.md`\n28: \n29: Do not load target-specific security skills before first mapping the source\n30: tree broadly. After broad structural mapping, you may consult target-specific\n31: skills only for reconnaissance checklists, not for vulnerability deep dives or\n32: finding generation.\n33: \n34: ## Mission\n35: \n36: Analyze the target under:\n37: \n38:     src/\n39: \n40: **Important Pathing Rule**: Your absolute workspace root is in your `<env>` block (`Workspace root folder`). Always prepend this to relative paths when using tools like `read`, `write`, or `edit`. Do NOT guess or hallucinate the root directory name.\n41: \n42: Infer:\n43: \n44: - target type,\n45: - languages,\n46: - frameworks and technologies,\n47: - repository structure,\n48: - build model,\n49: - execution model,\n50: - attack surfaces,\n51: - trust boundaries,\n52: - assets at risk,\n53: - dangerous sinks,\n54: - important data flows,\n55: - security assumptions,\n56: - interesting files,\n57: - validation model.\n58: \n59: ## Output files\n60: \n61: Phase 1 has two sub-stages:\n62: \n63: - Phase 1a: source reconnaissance.\n64: - Phase 1b: sandbox bootstrap.\n65: \n66: Both sub-stages must produce durable artifacts under `itemdb/notes/`.\n67: \n68: ### Phase 1a (recon notes)\n69: \n70: Create or update these required files:\n71: \n72:     itemdb/notes/target-profile.md\n73:     itemdb/notes/attack-surface.md\n74:     itemdb/notes/build-model.md\n75:     itemdb/notes/execution-model.md\n76:     itemdb/notes/trust-boundaries.md\n77:     itemdb/notes/data-flow.md\n78:     itemdb/notes/validation-model.md\n79:     itemdb/notes/interesting-files.md\n80:     itemdb/notes/security-assumptions.md\n81: \n82: Optional target-specific notes may also be created when useful:\n83: \n84:     itemdb/notes/auth-model.md\n85:     itemdb/notes/web-routes.md\n86:     itemdb/notes/cli-commands.md\n87:     itemdb/notes/public-api.md\n88:     itemdb/notes/cwe-map.md\n89:     itemdb/notes/benchmark-notes.md\n90:     itemdb/notes/crypto-usage.md\n91:     itemdb/notes/iac-resources.md\n92: \n93: ### Phase 1b (sandbox bootstrap)\n94: \n95: Required:\n96: \n97:     itemdb/notes/sandbox-plan.md\n98: \n99: Optional but expected when bootstrap actually runs:\n100: \n101:     sandbox/CODECOME-GENERATED.md\n102:     sandbox/<files derived from templates/sandboxes/<id>/>\n103: \n104: Phase 1b must run after Phase 1a in the same `make phase-1`\n105: invocation. Use `.opencode/skills/sandbox-bootstrap/SKILL.md` for the\n106: detailed decision flow, the manual fallback, the validation tiers,\n107: and the halt protocol.\n108: \n109: ## Reconnaissance rules\n110: \n111: 1. Do not assume the target is a web application.\n112: 2. Do not assume the target can be built or executed.\n113: 3. Do not assume the target type before inspecting the source tree.\n114: 4. Do not modify `src/`.\n115: 5. Do not create low-confidence vulnerability findings during reconnaissance.\n116: 6. Do not rely only on filenames, comments, or labels.\n117: 7. Be explicit about uncertainty.\n118: 8. Prefer concise, useful notes over exhaustive dumps.\n119: 9. Identify what later agents should review.\n120: 10. Identify how later validators can prove or disprove findings.\n121: 11. Do not load vulnerability-family-specific skills such as `sql-injection` during reconnaissance unless needed only to improve attack-surface terminology. Do not let any target-specific skill narrow the target model before broad mapping is complete.\n122: 12. Do not ask the user to choose Phase 2 scope during reconnaissance when a reasonable default can be inferred. Pick the primary target from repository evidence, document secondary surfaces as optional follow-up, and continue.\n123: 13. NEVER use the absolute path `/tmp/` for any files, downloads, or tool arguments. Always use workspace-relative `tmp/`.\n124: \n125: ## Target profile\n126: \n127: In `itemdb/notes/target-profile.md`, document:\n128: \n129: - detected target type,\n130: - confidence,\n131: - languages,\n132: - frameworks and technologies,\n133: - repository structure,\n134: - important manifests or build files,\n135: - target-specific observations.\n136: \n137: Possible target types:\n138: \n139: - web application,\n140: - backend service,\n141: - CLI tool,\n142: - library,\n143: - benchmark corpus,\n144: - infrastructure-as-code repository,\n145: - firmware tree,\n146: - desktop application,\n147: - mobile application,\n148: - mixed repository,\n149: - unknown.\n150: \n151: ## Attack surface\n152: \n153: In `itemdb/notes/attack-surface.md`, document detected attack surfaces.\n154: \n155: For each surface, include:\n156: \n157: - name,\n158: - type,\n159: - entrypoint,\n160: - input sources,\n161: - likely attacker control,\n162: - trust boundary,\n163: - relevant files,\n164: - likely vulnerability classes,\n165: - recommended follow-up.\n166: \n167: Examples of surfaces:\n168: \n169: - HTTP routes,\n170: - RPC methods,\n171: - CLI arguments,\n172: - stdin,\n173: - input files,\n174: - config files,\n175: - environment variables,\n176: - public library APIs,\n177: - message consumers,\n178: - webhooks,\n179: - file uploads,\n180: - archive extraction,\n181: - XML/YAML/JSON parsing,\n182: - template rendering,\n183: - shell command wrappers,\n184: - filesystem operations,\n185: - dynamic code loading,\n186: - authentication flows,\n187: - authorization decisions,\n188: - cryptographic operations,\n189: - network listeners,\n190: - benchmark testcase entrypoints.\n191: \n192: ## Build model\n193: \n194: In `itemdb/notes/build-model.md`, document:\n195: \n196: - build system,\n197: - build files,\n198: - likely build commands,\n199: - dependencies,\n200: - compiler/interpreter/runtime,\n201: - generated artifacts,\n202: - known blockers,\n203: - sandbox changes needed.\n204: \n205: ## Execution model\n206: \n207: In `itemdb/notes/execution-model.md`, document:\n208: \n209: - how the target appears to run,\n210: - entrypoints,\n211: - runtime dependencies,\n212: - config files,\n213: - environment variables,\n214: - ports,\n215: - databases,\n216: - queues,\n217: - external services,\n218: - test or benchmark harnesses.\n219: \n220: ## Trust boundaries\n221: \n222: In `itemdb/notes/trust-boundaries.md`, document places where lower-trust data or actors affect higher-trust behavior.\n223: \n224: Examples:\n225: \n226: - anonymous user to application,\n227: - authenticated user to tenant data,\n228: - regular user to admin function,\n229: - external webhook to internal job,\n230: - CLI user input to privileged operation,\n231: - input file to parser,\n232: - config file to service behavior,\n233: - user-controlled path to filesystem,\n234: - untrusted archive to extraction,\n235: - external identity provider to local session,\n236: - code to cryptographic signing operation.\n237: \n238: ## Data flow\n239: \n240: In `itemdb/notes/data-flow.md`, summarize security-relevant flows.\n241: \n242: Focus on:\n243: \n244: - untrusted input,\n245: - authentication,\n246: - authorization,\n247: - tenant isolation,\n248: - secret handling,\n249: - file paths,\n250: - external commands,\n251: - parsers,\n252: - serialization,\n253: - cryptography,\n254: - network calls,\n255: - memory unsafe operations.\n256: \n257: ## Validation model\n258: \n259: In `itemdb/notes/validation-model.md`, explain how findings can be validated.\n260: \n261: Include:\n262: \n263: - whether target can be built,\n264: - whether target can be run,\n265: - whether sandbox is sufficient,\n266: - useful commands,\n267: - useful test strategy,\n268: - useful sanitizer/debugger strategy,\n269: - what evidence should be captured,\n270: - blockers.\n271: \n272: ## Interesting files\n273: \n274: In `itemdb/notes/interesting-files.md`, list files and directories worth reviewing in Phase 2.\n275: \n276: For each item, include:\n277: \n278: - path,\n279: - reason,\n280: - likely vulnerability classes,\n281: - recommended follow-up.\n282: \n283: ## Security assumptions\n284: \n285: In `itemdb/notes/security-assumptions.md`, list assumptions using labels:\n286: \n287: - `confirmed`\n288: - `likely`\n289: - `unknown`\n290: - `risky`\n291: \n292: Example:\n293: \n294:     - [confirmed] The target contains C and C++ source files.\n295:     - [likely] Some testcases can be compiled independently.\n296:     - [unknown] The target has no complete documented build command yet.\n297:     - [risky] Several parser-like files perform manual buffer management.\n298: \n299: ## Phase 1b: Sandbox bootstrap\n300: \n301: After Phase 1a notes are complete, run Phase 1b in the same\n302: invocation. Goal: ensure `sandbox/` is a working validation\n303: environment for the target under `src/`.\n304: \n305: Mandatory output: `itemdb/notes/sandbox-plan.md`.\n306: \n307: Steps (full detail in `.opencode/skills/sandbox-bootstrap/SKILL.md`):\n308: \n309: 1. Inspect `sandbox/` state via `make sandbox-status` (or\n310:    `.venv/bin/python3 tools/sandbox-bootstrap.py status`).\n311: 2. Inspect existing `src/` runtime artifacts: `Dockerfile`,\n312:    `docker-compose.yml`, `Makefile`, `scripts/`, `README*`,\n313:    `INSTALL*`, `RUN*`, `docs/`. Decide what to honor.\n314: 3. Run `make sandbox-detect` to see ranked candidates from\n315:    `templates/sandboxes/`.\n316: 4. Choose one (or `multi-service-compose` if the target spans\n317:    several services).\n318: 5. If the `apply` and `validate` subcommands of\n319:    `tools/sandbox-bootstrap.py` are available, use them. If they\n320:    are not yet implemented (CLI exits with code 64), use the manual\n321:    fallback documented in the skill.\n322: 6. Substitute markers (`__VARNAME__`) using values from recon\n323:    notes and target documentation.\n324: 7. Run validation tiers (T1 sandbox setup, T2 sandbox start, T3\n325:    sandbox sanity, T4 target build, T5 target test, T6 sandbox\n326:    stop).\n327: 8. Write `sandbox/CODECOME-GENERATED.md` with provenance.\n328: 9. Update `itemdb/notes/sandbox-plan.md` with the validation\n329:    matrix, honoring decision, marker values, and any halt notice.\n330: \n331: If validation fails and remediation cannot succeed within the retry\n332: budget (default 3, configurable via\n333: `CODECOME_BOOTSTRAP_MAX_RETRIES`), halt and document the halt\n334: protocol in `sandbox-plan.md`.\n335: \n336: The default `validation_model` is `docker`. Use `static-only` or\n337: `nested-virt` only with explicit justification in `sandbox-plan.md`.\n338: \n339: ## Completion checklist\n340: \n341: Before finishing:\n342: \n343: Phase 1a:\n344: \n345: - all required notes exist,\n346: - target type is stated with confidence,\n347: - attack surfaces are listed,\n348: - build and execution model are documented,\n349: - validation model is documented,\n350: - interesting files are listed,\n351: - uncertainty is documented,\n352: - no low-quality findings were created,\n353: - a run summary is written when practical.\n354: \n355: Phase 1b:\n356: \n357: - `itemdb/notes/sandbox-plan.md` exists,\n358: - honoring decision is documented,\n359: - chosen example id is recorded,\n360: - marker values are listed,\n361: - validation matrix is filled in,\n362: - `validation_model` is stated,\n363: - if bootstrap halted, halt notice and required user inputs are\n364:   documented,\n365: - if bootstrap succeeded, `sandbox/CODECOME-GENERATED.md` exists\n366:   with provenance.\n367: \n368: Only describe user input as required when Phase 1b is blocked. For\n369: non-blocking preferences, use \"optional follow-up\" language and explain how\n370: the user can override the default with `PROMPT_EXTRA` or\n371: `PROMPT_EXTRA_FILE` on a later run.\n\n(End of file - total 371 lines)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"# CodeCome Recon Agent\n\nYou are the CodeCome Recon Agent.\n\nYour role is to perform target reconnaissance and attack surface recognition.\n\nYou do not create vulnerability findings unless explicitly instructed or unless an issue is extremely obvious, high-confidence, and security-relevant.\n\n**You must NEVER modify `codecome.yml`, `AGENTS.md`, Makefile, or any other project orchestration or configuration file. Your role is to perform reconnaissance on the target, not to reconfigure the project.**\n\nYour main output is a target model under:\n\n    itemdb/notes/\n\n## Required reading\n\nBefore starting reconnaissance, read:\n\n- `AGENTS.md`\n- `codecome.yml`","truncated":false,"loaded":[]},"title":".opencode/agents/recon.md","time":{"start":1779039180840,"end":1779039180863}},"id":"prt_e36ff9820001SyC5jA2FQ7pFgs","sessionID":"ses_1c900d483ffe3X7x4o8qKel0y4","messageID":"msg_e36ff7576001STkwn1Fu87q0ip"}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1779039180865,"sessionID":"ses_1c900d483ffe3X7x4o8qKel0y4","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_f317f8e542754973","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/pruiz/Develop/mine/CodeCome-e2e-testing/.opencode/skills/source-recon/SKILL.md"},"output":"<path>/Users/pruiz/Develop/mine/CodeCome-e2e-testing/.opencode/skills/source-recon/SKILL.md</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: # Source Reconnaissance Skill\n2: \n3: Use this skill during CodeCome Phase 1: target reconnaissance and attack surface recognition.\n4: \n5: The goal of reconnaissance is to understand the target before creating vulnerability findings.\n6: \n7: Do not rush into reporting bugs. First build a useful target model.\n8: \n9: ## Purpose\n10: \n11: Reconnaissance should answer:\n12: \n13: - What kind of target is this?\n14: - What languages and frameworks are used?\n15: - How is it built?\n16: - How is it executed?\n17: - What are the attack surfaces?\n18: - Where are the trust boundaries?\n19: - What assets are at risk?\n20: - What dangerous sinks exist?\n21: - How can findings be validated later?\n22: \n23: ## Output files\n24: \n25: Create or update these files under `itemdb/notes/`:\n26: \n27:     itemdb/notes/target-profile.md\n28:     itemdb/notes/attack-surface.md\n29:     itemdb/notes/build-model.md\n30:     itemdb/notes/execution-model.md\n31:     itemdb/notes/trust-boundaries.md\n32:     itemdb/notes/data-flow.md\n33:     itemdb/notes/validation-model.md\n34:     itemdb/notes/interesting-files.md\n35:     itemdb/notes/security-assumptions.md\n36: \n37: If the target has a specific nature, optional additional notes may be created.\n38: \n39: Examples:\n40: \n41:     itemdb/notes/web-routes.md\n42:     itemdb/notes/cli-commands.md\n43:     itemdb/notes/public-api.md\n44:     itemdb/notes/cwe-map.md\n45:     itemdb/notes/benchmark-notes.md\n46:     itemdb/notes/iac-resources.md\n47:     itemdb/notes/crypto-usage.md\n48:     itemdb/notes/auth-model.md\n49: \n50: ## Reconnaissance rules\n51: \n52: 1. Do not create findings during reconnaissance unless the issue is extremely obvious and high confidence.\n53: 2. Prefer broad understanding over deep analysis of one bug.\n54: 3. Identify what should be reviewed in later phases.\n55: 4. Be explicit about uncertainty.\n56: 5. Do not assume the target is a web application.\n57: 6. Do not assume the target can be executed.\n58: 7. Do not assume filenames or comments are reliable vulnerability evidence.\n59: 8. Do not modify source code.\n60: 9. Keep notes concise but useful.\n61: 10. Write notes as Markdown artifacts.\n62: \n63: ## Target type detection\n64: \n65: Infer the target type.\n66: \n67: Possible target types include:\n68: \n69: - web application,\n70: - backend service,\n71: - CLI tool,\n72: - library,\n73: - benchmark corpus,\n74: - infrastructure-as-code repository,\n75: - firmware tree,\n76: - desktop application,\n77: - mobile application,\n78: - mixed repository,\n79: - unknown.\n80: \n81: Use evidence such as:\n82: \n83: - repository structure,\n84: - manifest files,\n85: - build files,\n86: - routes/controllers,\n87: - command definitions,\n88: - package metadata,\n89: - Docker files,\n90: - CI configuration,\n91: - tests,\n92: - documentation,\n93: - source file extensions,\n94: - framework imports,\n95: - binary/build artifacts.\n96: \n97: ## Language and framework detection\n98: \n99: Identify relevant languages and technologies.\n100: \n101: Examples:\n102: \n103: - C/C++: Makefile, CMakeLists.txt, `.c`, `.cpp`, `.h`, `.hpp`\n104: - .NET: `.csproj`, `.sln`, ASP.NET controllers, `Program.cs`\n105: - Java: `pom.xml`, `build.gradle`, Spring annotations\n106: - Node: `package.json`, Express/Nest/Next files\n107: - Python: `pyproject.toml`, `requirements.txt`, Flask/FastAPI/Django\n108: - Go: `go.mod`, `cmd/`, `internal/`\n109: - PHP: `composer.json`, Laravel/Symfony structure\n110: - IaC: Terraform, Kubernetes YAML, Helm, Ansible, Salt, Nomad, Docker Compose\n111: \n112: ## Build model\n113: \n114: Document how the target appears to be built.\n115: \n116: Look for:\n117: \n118: - Makefiles,\n119: - CMake,\n120: - Gradle,\n121: - Maven,\n122: - npm/yarn/pnpm,\n123: - dotnet CLI,\n124: - Python packaging,\n125: - Go modules,\n126: - Dockerfiles,\n127: - CI scripts,\n128: - build documentation.\n129: \n130: Record:\n131: \n132: - likely build command,\n133: - required dependencies,\n134: - generated artifacts,\n135: - missing dependencies,\n136: - build uncertainty,\n137: - whether the sandbox needs adaptation.\n138: \n139: ## Execution model\n140: \n141: Document how the target appears to run.\n142: \n143: Examples:\n144: \n145: - HTTP server,\n146: - background worker,\n147: - CLI executable,\n148: - library imported by another program,\n149: - test harness,\n150: - benchmark testcase,\n151: - firmware image,\n152: - IaC deployment,\n153: - scheduled job,\n154: - message queue consumer.\n155: \n156: Record:\n157: \n158: - entrypoints,\n159: - runtime dependencies,\n160: - config files,\n161: - required environment variables,\n162: - ports,\n163: - local services,\n164: - databases,\n165: - queues,\n166: - external dependencies,\n167: - test commands.\n168: \n169: ## Attack surface recognition\n170: \n171: Identify attack surfaces.\n172: \n173: An attack surface is any externally influenced way to reach code, configuration, state, or behavior.\n174: \n175: Examples:\n176: \n177: - HTTP routes,\n178: - RPC methods,\n179: - GraphQL operations,\n180: - WebSocket handlers,\n181: - CLI arguments,\n182: - stdin,\n183: - input files,\n184: - uploaded files,\n185: - config files,\n186: - environment variables,\n187: - public library APIs,\n188: - message consumers,\n189: - webhooks,\n190: - scheduled jobs,\n191: - database migrations,\n192: - template rendering,\n193: - archive extraction,\n194: - XML parsing,\n195: - JSON/YAML deserialization,\n196: - filesystem paths,\n197: - external command invocation,\n198: - dynamic code loading,\n199: - authentication flows,\n200: - authorization decisions,\n201: - cryptographic operations,\n202: - signing operations,\n203: - network listeners,\n204: - IaC resources.\n205: \n206: For each attack surface, document:\n207: \n208: - name,\n209: - type,\n210: - entrypoints,\n211: - input sources,\n212: - likely attacker control,\n213: - relevant files,\n214: - trust boundary,\n215: - likely vulnerability classes.\n216: \n217: ## Trust boundaries\n218: \n219: Identify where data or control crosses from lower trust to higher trust.\n220: \n221: Examples:\n222: \n223: - anonymous user to application,\n224: - authenticated user to tenant data,\n225: - tenant A to tenant B,\n226: - regular user to admin operation,\n227: - external webhook to internal processing,\n228: - CLI argument to privileged operation,\n229: - input file to parser,\n230: - config file to service behavior,\n231: - network packet to parser,\n232: - user-controlled path to filesystem,\n233: - untrusted archive to extraction path,\n234: - untrusted template to renderer,\n235: - external identity provider to local session,\n236: - local code to HSM/signing operation.\n237: \n238: ## Assets at risk\n239: \n240: Identify assets that matter.\n241: \n242: Examples:\n243: \n244: - user data,\n245: - tenant data,\n246: - credentials,\n247: - API tokens,\n248: - private keys,\n249: - certificates,\n250: - signing keys,\n251: - session cookies,\n252: - database records,\n253: - filesystem contents,\n254: - generated documents,\n255: - audit logs,\n256: - admin actions,\n257: - internal network access,\n258: - compute resources,\n259: - service availability,\n260: - code execution context.\n261: \n262: ## Dangerous sinks\n263: \n264: Identify security-sensitive sinks.\n265: \n266: Examples:\n267: \n268: - SQL query construction,\n269: - shell command execution,\n270: - filesystem read/write/delete,\n271: - path normalization/joining,\n272: - archive extraction,\n273: - XML parsing,\n274: - YAML/object deserialization,\n275: - template rendering,\n276: - eval/dynamic code execution,\n277: - dynamic imports,\n278: - memory copy functions,\n279: - pointer arithmetic,\n280: - integer-size calculations,\n281: - cryptographic signing,\n282: - token validation,\n283: - password verification,\n284: - authorization decisions,\n285: - SSRF-capable HTTP clients,\n286: - LDAP queries,\n287: - XPath queries,\n288: - logging of secrets,\n289: - file upload storage,\n290: - privilege-changing operations.\n291: \n292: ## Data flow notes\n293: \n294: Capture important flows.\n295: \n296: Prioritize flows involving:\n297: \n298: - untrusted input,\n299: - authentication,\n300: - authorization,\n301: - tenant isolation,\n302: - secret handling,\n303: - file paths,\n304: - external commands,\n305: - parsers,\n306: - serialization,\n307: - crypto,\n308: - network calls,\n309: - memory unsafe operations.\n310: \n311: Do not attempt full formal data-flow analysis in Phase 1. Create useful notes for Phase 2.\n312: \n313: ## Security assumptions\n314: \n315: Record assumptions explicitly.\n316: \n317: Use these labels:\n318: \n319: - `confirmed`\n320: - `likely`\n321: - `unknown`\n322: - `risky`\n323: \n324: Examples:\n325: \n326:     - [likely] The service is intended to be exposed over HTTP.\n327:     - [unknown] It is unclear whether file paths come from authenticated users.\n328:     - [risky] Several shell command wrappers appear to accept string arguments.\n329:     - [confirmed] The target contains C code compiled with Make.\n330: \n331: ## Interesting files\n332: \n333: Create `itemdb/notes/interesting-files.md`.\n334: \n335: Include files that deserve deeper review.\n336: \n337: For each file or directory, record:\n338: \n339: - path,\n340: - why it is interesting,\n341: - likely vulnerability classes,\n342: - recommended follow-up.\n343: \n344: ## Validation model\n345: \n346: Create `itemdb/notes/validation-model.md`.\n347: \n348: Explain how findings can be validated.\n349: \n350: Examples:\n351: \n352: - build and run locally,\n353: - run unit tests,\n354: - create integration tests,\n355: - send HTTP requests,\n356: - call CLI commands,\n357: - craft input files,\n358: - run with sanitizers,\n359: - run under debugger,\n360: - compare benchmark oracle,\n361: - inspect generated configuration,\n362: - use static proof only.\n363: \n364: Include limitations and sandbox changes needed.\n365: \n366: ## Recommended phase 2 focus\n367: \n368: At the end of reconnaissance, provide a prioritized list of areas for hypothesis generation.\n369: \n370: Example:\n371: \n372:     1. Review authorization checks around document access.\n373:     2. Review file upload and archive extraction paths.\n374:     3. Review shell command wrappers.\n375:     4. Review XML parsing and deserialization.\n376:     5. Review C/C++ buffer handling in parser module.\n377: \n378: ## Completion checklist\n379: \n380: Before finishing reconnaissance, ensure that:\n381: \n382: - `target-profile.md` exists.\n383: - `attack-surface.md` exists.\n384: - `build-model.md` exists.\n385: - `execution-model.md` exists.\n386: - `trust-boundaries.md` exists.\n387: - `data-flow.md` exists.\n388: - `validation-model.md` exists.\n389: - `interesting-files.md` exists.\n390: - `security-assumptions.md` exists.\n391: - no low-quality findings were created prematurely.\n\n(End of file - total 391 lines)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"# Source Reconnaissance Skill\n\nUse this skill during CodeCome Phase 1: target reconnaissance and attack surface recognition.\n\nThe goal of reconnaissance is to understand the target before creating vulnerability findings.\n\nDo not rush into reporting bugs. First build a useful target model.\n\n## Purpose\n\nReconnaissance should answer:\n\n- What kind of target is this?\n- What languages and frameworks are used?\n- How is it built?\n- How is it executed?\n- What are the attack surfaces?\n- Where are the trust boundaries?\n- What assets are at risk?\n- What dangerous sinks exist?","truncated":false,"loaded":[]},"title":".opencode/skills/source-recon/SKILL.md","time":{"start":1779039180847,"end":1779039180864}},"id":"prt_e36ff982c001EkE4Pd2QR4xNCB","sessionID":"ses_1c900d483ffe3X7x4o8qKel0y4","messageID":"msg_e36ff7576001STkwn1Fu87q0ip"}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1779039180868,"sessionID":"ses_1c900d483ffe3X7x4o8qKel0y4","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_dc45a0387574d31a","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/pruiz/Develop/mine/CodeCome-e2e-testing/.opencode/skills/sandbox-bootstrap/SKILL.md"},"output":"<path>/Users/pruiz/Develop/mine/CodeCome-e2e-testing/.opencode/skills/sandbox-bootstrap/SKILL.md</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: # Sandbox Bootstrap Skill\n2: \n3: Use this skill during CodeCome **Phase 1b: Sandbox bootstrap**.\n4: \n5: Phase 1b runs immediately after Phase 1a (source reconnaissance) in\n6: the same `make phase-1` invocation. The goal is to ensure that\n7: `sandbox/` contains a working validation environment for the target\n8: under `src/`, so Phase 2 can rely on it.\n9: \n10: ## Templates are seeds, not finished sandboxes\n11: \n12: Every directory under `templates/sandboxes/<id>/` is a **seed**.\n13: Each seed ships only `Dockerfile`, `docker-compose.yml`, a starter\n14: `scripts/build.sh`, and a starter `scripts/test.sh`.\n15: \n16: That is on purpose. The agent is expected to extend the seed into a\n17: fully functional sandbox tailored to the specific target. Treating\n18: a seed as a finished sandbox is a workflow violation.\n19: \n20: You **must**:\n21: \n22: - implement the required sandbox capabilities (see \"Sandbox\n23:   capability contract\" below), preferably via helpers under\n24:   `sandbox/scripts/`,\n25: - adapt the starter `build.sh` and `test.sh` to the\n26:   real project layout (some targets nest their build under a\n27:   subdirectory of `src/`, not `src/` directly; many real targets do similar),\n28: - add target-specific scripts when they help (sanitizer builds,\n29:   fuzzing harnesses, debugger attach helpers, etc.),\n30: - make every script executable,\n31: - document every authored or adapted script in\n32:   `itemdb/notes/sandbox-plan.md`.\n33: \n34: You **must not**:\n35: \n36: - record a validation tier as `skipped` because its script is\n37:   absent,\n38: - replace authoring a script with an in-chat manual spot-check\n39:   (manual checks are not durable and do not survive the next\n40:   `make phase-1` run),\n41: - assume that \"the template ships only X\" means \"only X is\n42:   expected to exist\".\n43: \n44: ## Sandbox capability contract\n45: \n46: Phase 1b does not require one universal fixed script set. Different\n47: targets need different mechanics. What matters is that the resulting\n48: `sandbox/` exposes a coherent set of capabilities.\n49: \n50: Required capabilities for a Phase 2-ready sandbox:\n51: \n52: | Capability | Preferred helper | Purpose |\n53: |---|---|---|\n54: | sandbox setup | `sandbox/scripts/setup.sh` | Set up the sandbox environment in a repeatable way. This may build a container image, prepare a VM image, assemble a firmware bundle, or perform equivalent environment preparation. |\n55: | sandbox start | `sandbox/scripts/up.sh` | Bring the sandbox environment up when runtime startup is distinct from setup. |\n56: | sandbox sanity | `sandbox/scripts/check.sh` | Verify mounts, toolchain/runtime availability, and basic health. |\n57: | target build | `sandbox/scripts/build.sh` | Build the target inside the sandbox when applicable. |\n58: | target test | `sandbox/scripts/test.sh` | Run the target tests inside the sandbox when applicable. |\n59: | sandbox stop | `sandbox/scripts/down.sh` | Tear the sandbox environment down cleanly. |\n60: \n61: ## Realistic runtime model\n62: \n63: Phase 1b should aim for the most realistic local runtime environment\n64: that is reasonably derivable from the repository, not merely a\n65: toolchain container that can build the source.\n66: \n67: What \"realistic\" means depends on target type:\n68: \n69: - **Web application / API / backend service** — prefer a sandbox that\n70:   starts the real application process and any inferable dependencies\n71:   (database, cache, queue, reverse proxy) rather than only compiling\n72:   the code.\n73: - **DB-backed app** — when docs/manifests show a database is required,\n74:   prefer including the database service, schema setup, migrations,\n75:   and minimal seed data when they are reasonably available.\n76: - **Queue / worker system** — include the worker and broker only when\n77:   they materially affect the reachable attack surface.\n78: - **CLI / library / static target** — do not invent a web server just\n79:   to look realistic; the closest faithful runtime may still be a\n80:   build-and-run CLI sandbox or `static-only`.\n81: - **Targets with cloud-only or third-party dependencies** — stub or\n82:   mock them only when a local replacement is straightforward and the\n83:   behavior is relevant to validation. Otherwise document the gap.\n84: \n85: When deciding whether to include a dependency, prefer source-backed\n86: signals such as:\n87: \n88: - `src/docker-compose.yml` / `src/compose.yml`,\n89: - framework config files,\n90: - migration files,\n91: - `.env.example`,\n92: - `README*` / `docs/` runbooks,\n93: - manifests for services like PostgreSQL, MySQL, Redis, RabbitMQ,\n94:   Nginx, Apache, PHP-FPM, etc.\n95: \n96: Do not stop at a toolchain-only or build-only sandbox when Phase 4 or\n97: Phase 5 validation would realistically need a running app. If full\n98: runtime is not feasible, produce the closest faithful approximation\n99: and document why in `sandbox-plan.md`.\n100: \n101: Recommended helper scripts when a realistic runtime model applies:\n102: \n103: - `migrate.sh` — apply schema migrations or other one-time DB\n104:   setup.\n105: - `seed.sh` — load minimal fixture data needed for realistic\n106:   validation.\n107: - `healthcheck.sh` — verify that the real app is serving,\n108:   connected, and usable (HTTP health route, root page, CLI smoke\n109:   command, DB ping, etc.).\n110: - `run.sh` — drive the target with a representative runtime\n111:   invocation when the standard test suite is not enough.\n112: \n113: Recommended helper capabilities when the target/runtime model makes\n114: them useful (these are not part of the Phase 2 gate, but are\n115: strongly encouraged):\n116: \n117: | Capability | Preferred helper | Purpose |\n118: |---|---|---|\n119: | sandbox shell | `sandbox/scripts/shell.sh` | Open a shell in the sandbox. |\n120: | sandbox logs | `sandbox/scripts/logs.sh` | Inspect runtime logs. |\n121: | sandbox clean | `sandbox/scripts/clean.sh` | Remove containers, volumes, and tmp produced by validation. |\n122: | sandbox reset | `sandbox/scripts/reset.sh` | Recreate the environment from a clean state. |\n123: \n124: If a recommended helper does not apply, say so explicitly in\n125: `sandbox-plan.md`. Do not silently omit it.\n126: \n127: Add additional scripts whenever the target benefits, for example:\n128: \n129: - `run.sh` — drive the target with a sample input.\n130: - `build-asan.sh` — build with AddressSanitizer + UBSan.\n131: - `fuzz.sh` — seed a fuzzing corpus or drive a fuzzer.\n132: - `attach-debugger.sh` — attach gdb / lldb to a running container.\n133: \n134: Naming convention for extras:\n135: \n136: - prefer single-word names when the meaning is unambiguous (`migrate`,\n137:   `seed`, `healthcheck`, `run`, `fuzz`),\n138: - use `<verb>-<flavor>.sh` for build flavors (e.g. `build-asan.sh`,\n139:   `build-ubsan.sh`) so the canonical `build.sh` keeps its meaning,\n140: - use a descriptive multi-word name when no short form is unambiguous\n141:   (e.g. `attach-debugger.sh`),\n142: - never reuse the canonical names (`setup`, `up`, `check`, `build`,\n143:   `test`, `down`, `shell`, `logs`, `clean`, `reset`) for variants;\n144:   use a prefix or suffix instead.\n145: \n146: Document any extras in `itemdb/notes/sandbox-plan.md` under \"Extra\n147: scripts authored\", with one line per script explaining what it does\n148: and how to run it.\n149: \n150: ## Authoring conventions for helper scripts\n151: \n152: - All helper scripts are bash with `set -euo pipefail` at the top.\n153: - Path discipline: paths inside the container start with\n154:   `/workspace/...`; paths on the host start with `sandbox/...`.\n155: - Idempotency: `down.sh`, `clean.sh`, and `reset.sh` should be safe\n156:   to run repeatedly even when the stack is already down.\n157: - `check.sh` runs **inside the sandbox container**, exercising the\n158:   toolchain (compiler versions, package manager versions, language\n159:   runtime versions) and verifying the expected workspace mounts\n160:   exist (`/workspace/src`, `/workspace/itemdb`, `/workspace/sandbox`,\n161:   `/workspace/AGENTS.md`, `/workspace/codecome.yml`).\n162: - `setup.sh` should prepare the sandbox environment without implying\n163:   the environment must be started. When Docker Compose is used, it\n164:   should typically run `docker compose -f sandbox/docker-compose.yml\n165:   build`.\n166: - `up.sh` runs `docker compose -f sandbox/docker-compose.yml up -d\n167:   --build` (or the multi-service variant) when the sandbox needs a\n168:   long-lived environment. If the target does not need a persistent\n169:   started stack, explain that in `sandbox-plan.md`.\n170: - `shell.sh` runs `docker compose -f sandbox/docker-compose.yml\n171:   exec <service> bash` or `docker compose run --rm <service>\n172:   bash`.\n173: - `logs.sh` runs `docker compose -f sandbox/docker-compose.yml\n174:   logs -f`.\n175: - `clean.sh` runs `docker compose -f sandbox/docker-compose.yml\n176:   down -v` and removes any `tmp/` artifacts produced by the\n177:   sandbox.\n178: - `reset.sh` is `clean.sh` followed by `up.sh`, or a tighter\n179:   per-target reset when faster.\n180: \n181: ## T1/T2/T3/T4/T5/T6 reporting rules\n182: \n183: - T1 must never be recorded as `skipped` because the sandbox setup\n184:   mechanism is missing. Prefer `setup.sh`; `docker compose\n185:   -f sandbox/docker-compose.yml build` is an acceptable fallback.\n186: - T2 must never be recorded as `skipped` because the sandbox start\n187:   mechanism is missing when the sandbox requires startup. Prefer\n188:   `up.sh`.\n189: - T3 must never be recorded as `skipped` because the sandbox sanity\n190:   mechanism is missing. Prefer `check.sh`.\n191: - T4/T5 may legitimately be `skipped` only when the target\n192:   genuinely has no build or test step. The reason must be in\n193:   `sandbox-plan.md` (`static-only`, pre-built firmware, header-only\n194:   library, etc.).\n195: - T6 must never be recorded as `skipped` because the sandbox stop /\n196:   teardown mechanism is missing. Prefer `down.sh`.\n197: - A manual in-chat toolchain check is not a substitute for\n198:   `check.sh`.\n199: \n200: `tools/sandbox-bootstrap.py validate` enforces these rules for the\n201: required Phase 2 capabilities: a missing setup, start, check,\n202: build, test, or stop mechanism is reported as **failed** (not\n203: skipped). The Phase 2 gate blocks on `failed`.\n204: \n205: ## Purpose\n206: \n207: Phase 1b answers:\n208: \n209: - Does `sandbox/` already work for this target?\n210: - If not, which curated example under `templates/sandboxes/<id>/` is\n211:   the best starting point?\n212: - Does the target ship its own `Dockerfile`, `docker-compose.yml`,\n213:   or runbooks under `src/` that should be honored?\n214: - What marker values are correct for this target (versions, ports,\n215:   target name)?\n216: - Did the validation tiers actually pass?\n217: - If not, what does the user need to do to unblock Phase 2?\n218: \n219: ## Required output\n220: \n221: Write or update:\n222: \n223:     itemdb/notes/sandbox-plan.md\n224: \n225: This is the durable artifact. Do not leave Phase 1b decisions only\n226: in chat history.\n227: \n228: Mandatory sections in `sandbox-plan.md`:\n229: \n230: 1. **Detected stack** — languages, manifests, and runtime services\n231:    inferred from Phase 1a notes.\n232: 2. **Honoring decision** — what `src/` artifacts were honored,\n233:    wrapped, or ignored, and why. Mandatory even when nothing is\n234:    honored (\"nothing to honor\").\n235: 3. **Chosen example(s)** — id from `templates/sandboxes/`.\n236: 4. **Marker values applied** — table of `__VARNAME__` → value.\n237: 5. **Runtime model** — one of: `full-runtime`, `partial-runtime`,\n238:    `build-only`, `static-only`, `nested-virt`. Explain why this is\n239:    the closest faithful runtime model for the target.\n240: 6. **Services started** — app, web server, database, cache, queue,\n241:    broker, reverse proxy, or other runtime services that the sandbox\n242:    actually starts. If a service was expected but omitted, say so and\n243:    explain why.\n244: 7. **Health / smoke checks** — the exact commands or requests used to\n245:    verify the target is actually runnable (HTTP request, root page,\n246:    CLI smoke command, DB ping, migration status, etc.).\n247: 8. **Known runtime gaps** — secrets, external services, cloud-only\n248:    dependencies, hardware, or other blockers that prevent a more\n249:    realistic local stack.\n250: 9. **Validation matrix** — for each tier (T1 sandbox setup, T2\n251:    sandbox start, T3 sandbox sanity, T4 target build, T5 target\n252:    test, T6 sandbox stop): pass/fail/skipped, last command, exit\n253:    code, last 50 lines of stderr.\n254: 10. **`validation_model`** — one of: `docker`, `static-only`,\n255:    `nested-virt`. Justification mandatory for the last two.\n256: 11. **Remediation log** — each automatic remediation attempt with its\n257:    rationale and outcome.\n258: 12. **Open questions for the user** — optional, only if input is\n259:    needed.\n260: 13. **Halt notice** — only when bootstrap could not finish.\n261: \n262: ## Tooling\n263: \n264: The bootstrap CLI lives at `tools/sandbox-bootstrap.py` and is also\n265: exposed via Make targets:\n266: \n267: | CLI subcommand | Make target | Status |\n268: |---|---|---|\n269: | `list` | `make sandbox-list` | available |\n270: | `inspect <id>` | `make sandbox-inspect ID=<id>` | available |\n271: | `detect` | `make sandbox-detect` | available |\n272: | `status [--gate]` | `make sandbox-status` | available |\n273: | `apply <id>` | `make sandbox-bootstrap ID=<id>` | available |\n274: | `regenerate` | `make sandbox-regenerate` | available |\n275: | `validate` | `make sandbox-validate` | available |\n276: \n277: When a subcommand is \"not yet implemented\" the CLI exits with code\n278: `64`. All Phase 1b subcommands are now implemented; if you ever\n279: hit code 64, refer to `.project/auto-sandbox-bootstrap-plan.md`.\n280: \n281: Always invoke the CLI through the project's virtualenv:\n282: \n283:     .venv/bin/python3 tools/sandbox-bootstrap.py <subcommand>\n284: \n285: Or via the Make targets when running from the project root.\n286: \n287: ## Decision flow\n288: \n289: ```\n290: Phase 1a complete\n291:         |\n292:         v\n293: read itemdb/notes/* for stack hints\n294:         |\n295:         v\n296: inspect sandbox/ state\n297:    |        |        |\n298: empty   tracked   user-managed\n299:    |        |        |\n300:    |        v        v\n301:    |   try-validate-existing\n302:    |        |        |\n303:    |     passes   fails\n304:    |        |        |\n305:    v        v        v\n306: choose example -> apply -> validate -> done\n307:                               |\n308:                           on failure\n309:                               |\n310:                           remediate\n311:                               |\n312:                        within retry budget?\n313:                               |\n314:                             yes/no\n315:                               |\n316:                               v\n317:                          halt + sandbox-plan.md\n318: ```\n319: \n320: ## Inputs to consult before choosing\n321: \n322: Always read these files before deciding:\n323: \n324: - `itemdb/notes/target-profile.md`\n325: - `itemdb/notes/build-model.md`\n326: - `itemdb/notes/execution-model.md`\n327: - `itemdb/notes/interesting-files.md`\n328: - `itemdb/notes/validation-model.md`\n329: - `src/Dockerfile`\n330: - `src/docker-compose.yml` and `src/docker-compose.yaml`\n331: - `src/compose.yml` and `src/compose.yaml`\n332: - `src/Makefile`\n333: - `src/scripts/`\n334: - `src/README*`\n335: - `src/CONTRIBUTING*`\n336: - `src/INSTALL*`\n337: - `src/RUN*`\n338: - `src/docs/`\n339: \n340: ## Honoring `src/` artifacts\n341: \n342: If `src/` contains usable runtime definitions, honor them. The\n343: `multi-service-compose` example is built around this case: its build\n344: and test scripts pass `src/docker-compose.yml` as a second `-f`\n345: argument so the user's compose remains authoritative.\n346: \n347: Honoring rules:\n348: \n349: 1. If `src/Dockerfile` defines the runtime, use it via the\n350:    `multi-service-compose` example or by referencing it from a\n351:    thin sandbox wrapper. Do not duplicate it.\n352: 2. If `src/docker-compose.yml` is present and runnable, prefer\n353:    layering on top of it via `multi-service-compose`.\n354: 3. If `src/Makefile` describes the build, the language-specific\n355:    example's `scripts/build.sh` should call it instead of\n356:    re-implementing build logic.\n357: 4. If `src/README*` or `src/docs/` describe ports, environment\n358:    variables, or run commands, capture those values into marker\n359:    substitutions or directly into the generated `sandbox/` files.\n360: 5. If `src/` artifacts exist but are clearly inappropriate\n361:    (production secrets, cloud-only behavior, build-time-only\n362:    helpers), document the reason in `sandbox-plan.md` under\n363:    \"Honoring decision\" and proceed with the curated example.\n364: \n365: ## Build-time vs runtime stacks\n366: \n367: A repository can contain build-time helpers (e.g. a Node.js layer\n368: that produces static assets consumed by a Python runtime). Those\n369: helpers should not be expressed as runtime services in the sandbox.\n370: Treat them as multi-stage build steps inside the runtime example's\n371: `Dockerfile`, or as one-off `docker compose run` invocations rather\n372: than always-on services.\n373: \n374: ## Marker substitution\n375: \n376: Examples use `__VARNAME__` markers. The agent fills the values from:\n377: \n378: 1. recon notes (e.g. exact Python version from `build-model.md`),\n379: 2. target documentation in `src/`,\n380: 3. sensible defaults if nothing else is known.\n381: \n382: Two ways to substitute markers:\n383: \n384: - Pass `--var KEY=VAL` to `tools/sandbox-bootstrap.py apply` once\n385:   it is implemented.\n386: - Edit the copied files in `sandbox/` directly. This is the\n387:   manual fallback below.\n388: \n389: Do not invent variables that are not defined in `manifest.yml`.\n390: \n391: ## Preferred flow (using the CLI)\n392: \n393: 1. Run `make sandbox-detect` to see ranked candidates.\n394: 2. Run `make sandbox-inspect ID=<chosen-example>` to see the\n395:    manifest, file list, and markers.\n396: 3. Run `make sandbox-status` to see if `sandbox/` is empty,\n397:    user-managed, or generated.\n398: 4. If `sandbox/` is user-managed (no `CODECOME-GENERATED.md`) and\n399:    Phase 2 will run, attempt validation against the existing\n400:    scripts first. If it passes, capture the result in\n401:    `sandbox-plan.md` and move on. If it fails, halt with the halt\n402:    protocol and request user guidance — do not silently overwrite\n403:    user-managed content.\n404: 5. To bootstrap a fresh sandbox, prefer:\n405: \n406:        BOOTSTRAP_ARGS='--var KEY1=VAL1 --var KEY2=VAL2' \\\n407:          make sandbox-bootstrap ID=<chosen-example>\n408: \n409:    Or, if invoking the CLI directly:\n410: \n411:        .venv/bin/python3 tools/sandbox-bootstrap.py apply <id> \\\n412:          --var KEY1=VAL1 --var KEY2=VAL2\n413: \n414:    Use `--dry-run` first to preview which files would be written\n415:    and which markers are still unfilled. Use `--force` only when\n416:    `sandbox/` has user-managed content that the user has accepted\n417:    to lose (the prior content will be moved to\n418:    `sandbox/.backup-<timestamp>/`).\n419: \n420: 6. To re-apply after a manifest update or a marker change:\n421: \n422:        make sandbox-regenerate\n423:        # or with overrides:\n424:        BOOTSTRAP_ARGS='--var PYTHON_VERSION=3.13' make sandbox-regenerate\n425: \n426:    Regenerate reads `sandbox/CODECOME-GENERATED.md` for the source\n427:    example id and the previous markers. CLI overrides win. The\n428:    prior sandbox content is always moved to a fresh\n429:    `sandbox/.backup-<timestamp>/`.\n430: \n431: 7. Run validation tiers:\n432: \n433:        make sandbox-validate\n434: \n435:    Or with options:\n436: \n437:        BOOTSTRAP_ARGS='--keep-going' make sandbox-validate\n438:        BOOTSTRAP_ARGS='--scripts-only' make sandbox-validate\n439:        BOOTSTRAP_ARGS='--docker-only' make sandbox-validate\n440: \n441:    `validate` writes a \"Validation run <ISO>\" Markdown table at the\n442:    end of `sandbox/CODECOME-GENERATED.md` so each run is auditable.\n443:    Use the JSON output (`--format json`) when scripting the agent\n444:    loop:\n445: \n446:        .venv/bin/python3 tools/sandbox-bootstrap.py --format json \\\n447:          validate --keep-going\n448: \n449: ## Validation tiers\n450: \n451: | Tier | Purpose | Preferred helper | Fallback |\n452: |---|---|---|---|\n453: | T1 | Sandbox setup | `sandbox/scripts/setup.sh` | `docker compose -f sandbox/docker-compose.yml build` |\n454: | T2 | Sandbox start | `sandbox/scripts/up.sh` | none — implement it when startup is distinct from build |\n455: | T3 | Sanity | `sandbox/scripts/check.sh` | none — implement it |\n456: | T4 | Target build | `sandbox/scripts/build.sh` (template ships starter; adapt it) | none — implement it |\n457: | T5 | Target test | `sandbox/scripts/test.sh` (template ships starter; adapt it) | none — implement it |\n458: | T6 | Sandbox stop | `sandbox/scripts/down.sh` | none — implement it |\n459: \n460: For each tier capture: start time, exit code, last 50 lines of\n461: combined stdout+stderr, duration, outcome\n462: (`passed | failed | skipped`).\n463: \n464: A missing required capability causes the tier to record `failed`,\n465: **not** `skipped`. The Phase 2 gate blocks on `failed`.\n466: \n467: `skipped` is reserved for tiers that genuinely do not apply to the\n468: target (e.g. `static-only` builds with no executable). Such cases\n469: require a positive justification in `sandbox-plan.md`.\n470: \n471: Per-tier failures must be triaged. Do not move to the next tier on\n472: T1/T2/T3 failure unless the user explicitly asks for `--keep-going`.\n473: \n474: ## Auto-remediation\n475: \n476: The agent may attempt automatic remediations when validation fails.\n477: Default budget is 3 attempts; honor the `CODECOME_BOOTSTRAP_MAX_RETRIES`\n478: environment variable when present.\n479: \n480: Each attempt must:\n481: \n482: 1. State the failure cause hypothesis.\n483: 2. State what is being changed (file, line range, intent).\n484: 3. Re-run validation tiers from where the failure occurred.\n485: 4. Record the attempt in the remediation log of `sandbox-plan.md`.\n486: \n487: Common remediations:\n488: \n489: - Adjust the Debian or language base tag.\n490: - Add a missing native dev package to the Dockerfile.\n491: - Adjust an exposed port marker.\n492: - Replace a hard-coded build command with the one from\n493:   `src/Makefile` or `build-model.md`.\n494: - Drop a useless `EXPOSE` directive when the target has no app\n495:   port.\n496: \n497: Stop conditions:\n498: \n499: - Retry budget exhausted.\n500: - Failure requires user input that the agent does not have (secret,\n501:   external service, hardware device).\n502: - Failure is outside the sandbox (Docker not installed on host,\n503:   insufficient disk space, etc.).\n504: \n505: When stopping, write the halt notice to `sandbox-plan.md`.\n506: \n507: ## Halt protocol\n508: \n509: When bootstrap cannot finish, `sandbox-plan.md` must include:\n510: \n511: 1. **Attempts** — every remediation step with command and exit\n512:    code.\n513: 2. **Root cause hypothesis** — concise diagnosis.\n514: 3. **What is needed from the user** — the exact missing input.\n515: 4. **Suggested next action** — copy-pasteable.\n516: 5. **Halt notice** — explicit \"Phase 2 blocked until this is\n517:    resolved\" statement.\n518: 6. **Override hint** — mention `CODECOME_ALLOW_NO_SANDBOX=1` for\n519:    users who want to proceed despite the missing sandbox.\n520: \n521: ## Special validation models\n522: \n523: Some targets cannot be exercised by Docker alone.\n524: \n525: ### `static-only`\n526: \n527: Use when the target cannot be executed in the local sandbox. Possible\n528: reasons: corpus too large to build, no executable artifacts, license\n529: restriction, cross-compiled firmware that the host cannot run, or a\n530: binary-only edge case where review is purely static.\n531: \n532: Required justification section in `sandbox-plan.md`:\n533: \n534:     ## Justification: static-only\n535: \n536:     - <reason>\n537:     - <evidence from recon notes>\n538: \n539: Phase 2 gate honors `static-only` only when the justification is\n540: present.\n541: \n542: ### `nested-virt`\n543: \n544: Use when the target genuinely requires nested virtualization. Apply\n545: the `templates/sandboxes/nested-virt/` example. Document in\n546: `sandbox-plan.md`:\n547: \n548:     ## Justification: nested-virt\n549: \n550:     - <reason>\n551:     - <required QEMU arch>\n552:     - <KVM availability statement>\n553: \n554: ## Idempotency rules\n555: \n556: 1. Never overwrite a non-generated `sandbox/` silently. Detect by\n557:    the absence of `sandbox/CODECOME-GENERATED.md` plus tracked\n558:    user content.\n559: 2. Always back up displaced files into\n560:    `sandbox/.backup-<timestamp>/` before modifying.\n561: 3. The provenance file must reflect the latest applied example and\n562:    its markers.\n563: \n564: ## Reading `.env` files\n565: \n566: - `sandbox/.env` is generated by CodeCome during bootstrap and may be read as\n567:   runtime metadata (for example `COMPOSE_PROJECT_NAME`).\n568: - `.env` and `.env.*` files under `src/**` are part of target input and may be\n569:   read during audit/recon when relevant.\n570: - Do not read unrelated `.env` files elsewhere in the workspace.\n571: \n572: ## When to ask the user\n573: \n574: Ask only for blocking information. Do not ask for things that can be\n575: inferred from notes or `src/` artifacts. Do not ask for preferences when a\n576: safe default can be chosen and documented. For non-blocking preferences,\n577: choose a default, document the rationale in `sandbox-plan.md`, and mention\n578: that the user can override it with `PROMPT_EXTRA` or `PROMPT_EXTRA_FILE`.\n579: \n580: Examples of legitimate blocking asks:\n581: \n582: - \"The repo references a private gem server. Should I skip those\n583:   dependencies for review purposes, or do you have a `bundler`\n584:   config to mount?\"\n585: - \"The target uses `qemu-system-arm`. Is KVM available on the host?\n586:   If not, runtime validation will be slow.\"\n587: \n588: For non-blocking defaults, avoid \"User input requested\" language. Use\n589: \"Optional follow-up\" and keep Phase 1 moving.\n590: \n591: If the missing input blocks Phase 1b, write it in `sandbox-plan.md` using\n592: the halt protocol. The user reads the plan and can rerun with additional\n593: context through `PROMPT_EXTRA` or `PROMPT_EXTRA_FILE`.\n\n(End of file - total 593 lines)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"# Sandbox Bootstrap Skill\n\nUse this skill during CodeCome **Phase 1b: Sandbox bootstrap**.\n\nPhase 1b runs immediately after Phase 1a (source reconnaissance) in\nthe same `make phase-1` invocation. The goal is to ensure that\n`sandbox/` contains a working validation environment for the target\nunder `src/`, so Phase 2 can rely on it.\n\n## Templates are seeds, not finished sandboxes\n\nEvery directory under `templates/sandboxes/<id>/` is a **seed**.\nEach seed ships only `Dockerfile`, `docker-compose.yml`, a starter\n`scripts/build.sh`, and a starter `scripts/test.sh`.\n\nThat is on purpose. The agent is expected to extend the seed into a\nfully functional sandbox tailored to the specific target. Treating\na seed as a finished sandbox is a workflow violation.\n\nYou **must**:","truncated":false,"loaded":[]},"title":".opencode/skills/sandbox-bootstrap/SKILL.md","time":{"start":1779039180852,"end":1779039180866}},"id":"prt_e36ff98300017JHiWs1u0WqLoZ","sessionID":"ses_1c900d483ffe3X7x4o8qKel0y4","messageID":"msg_e36ff7576001STkwn1Fu87q0ip"}}
