{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1779039312252,"sessionID":"ses_1c900d483ffe3X7x4o8qKel0y4","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"write","callID":"call_66ce3d29a0a2d4c2","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/pruiz/Develop/mine/CodeCome-e2e-testing/itemdb/notes/trust-boundaries.md","content":"# Trust Boundaries\n\n## Overview\n\nThis document identifies where lower-trust data or actors affect higher-trust behavior.\n\n## Trust Boundaries\n\n### 1. CLI User Input → Application\n\n| Attribute | Details |\n|-----------|---------|\n| **Boundary** | External CLI user input → CLI application |\n| **Direction** | Untrusted → Trusted |\n| **Input** | `argv[1]`, `argv[2]` |\n| **Processing** | Command dispatch in `main()` |\n| **Risk** | Attacker controls command and arguments |\n\n**Example**: User provides `./bin/sample-c-cli remove /etc/passwd`\n\n### 2. User String → Greeting Output\n\n| Attribute | Details |\n|-----------|---------|\n| **Boundary** | User-controlled string → stdout |\n| **Direction** | Untrusted → Trusted output |\n| **Input** | `name` argument to `greet_user()` |\n| **Processing** | Buffer copy in `greet_user()` |\n| **Risk** | Buffer overflow if name exceeds buffer size |\n\n**Example**: `./bin/sample-c-cli greet AAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAA`\n\n### 3. User String → Format String\n\n| Attribute | Details |\n|-----------|---------|\n| **Boundary** | User-controlled string → printf format string |\n| **Direction** | Untrusted → Trusted output function |\n| **Input** | `message` argument to `echo_message()` |\n| **Processing** | Direct `printf(message)` call |\n| **Risk** | Format string vulnerability allows memory read |\n\n**Example**: `./bin/sample-c-cli echo %s%s%s%s`\n\n### 4. User String → Shell Command\n\n| Attribute | Details |\n|-----------|---------|\n| **Boundary** | User-controlled path → shell command execution |\n| **Direction** | Untrusted → Trusted shell execution |\n| **Input** | `path` argument to `remove_file()` |\n| **Processing** | `system(\"rm -f \" + path)` |\n| **Risk** | OS command injection |\n\n**Example**: `./bin/sample-c-cli remove \"/etc/passwd; cat /etc/shadow\"`\n\n### 5. User Path → Filesystem Operation\n\n| Attribute | Details |\n|-----------|---------|\n| **Boundary** | User-controlled path → filesystem delete operation |\n| **Direction** | Untrusted → Trusted filesystem |\n| **Input** | `path` argument to `remove_file()` |\n| **Processing** | `rm -f` shell command |\n| **Risk** | Arbitrary file deletion |\n\n**Example**: `./bin/sample-c-cli remove \"~/.ssh/authorized_keys\"`\n\n## Summary\n\n| Boundary | From | To | Risk Level |\n|----------|------|-----|-------------|\n| CLI args → App | User input | CLI execution | Low |\n| String → Greeting | User string | Buffer copy | Medium |\n| String → Format | User string | printf format | High |\n| String → Shell | User string | system() call | Critical |\n| Path → Filesystem | User path | rm command | Critical |\n\n## Security Impact\n\nThe `remove` command boundary is the most critical — it allows an attacker to execute arbitrary shell commands by providing a crafted path argument. The `echo` command is also high-risk due to format string vulnerability."},"output":"Wrote file successfully.","metadata":{"diagnostics":{},"filepath":"/Users/pruiz/Develop/mine/CodeCome-e2e-testing/itemdb/notes/trust-boundaries.md","exists":false,"truncated":false},"title":"itemdb/notes/trust-boundaries.md","time":{"start":1779039312241,"end":1779039312249}},"id":"prt_e3701996d001FvQiWVocTSXG6Y","sessionID":"ses_1c900d483ffe3X7x4o8qKel0y4","messageID":"msg_e37013f88001vxWbI8WyzmwVOT"}}
